        <exercise id="fs-id3069160" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2000830"><para id="import-auto-id3007464">A certain hydraulic system is designed to exert a force 100 times as large as the one put into it. (a) What must be the ratio of the area of the wheel cylinder to the area of the pedal cylinder? (b) What must be the ratio of their diameters? (c) By what factor is the distance through which the output force moves reduced relative to the distance through which the input force moves? Assume no losses to friction.</para></problem></exercise>
        <exercise id="fs-id2452595" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1927445"><para id="import-auto-id3101875">(a) Verify that work input equals work output for a hydraulic system assuming no losses to friction. Do this by showing that the distance the output force moves is reduced by the same factor that the output force is increased. Assume the volume of the fluid is constant. (b) What effect would friction within the fluid and between components in the system have on the output force? How would this depend on whether or not the fluid is moving?</para>
